|extlinks=yes
|x=
}}

{{Science}}

==A==

{{glossary}}
<span id="absolute humidity"></span>{{term|term='''[[absolute humidity]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The mass of water vapor in the atmosphere per unit of volume of space.<ref name="IIP 2008">{{cite web |author=Bureau of International Information Programs (IIP) |authorlink=Bureau of International Information Programs |title=Glossary: An Outline of American Geography |website=america.gov |date=2008-06-26 |url=https://www.america.gov/st/diversity-english/2008/May/20080618220306eaifas0.30677.html |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20080626032146/https://www.america.gov/st/diversity-english/2008/May/20080618220306eaifas0.30677.html |archive-date=2008-06-26 |dead-url=yes |publisher=[[United States Department of State]] |location=Washington, DC}}</ref>}}

<span id="absolute location"></span>{{term|term='''[[absolute location]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The {{gli|location}} of a point on the Earth's surface that can be expressed by a grid reference such as {{gli|latitude}} and {{gli|longitude}}.<ref name="OERI 1996">{{Citation |url=http://www2.ed.gov/pubs/parents/Geography/glossary.html |title=Archived: Helping Your Child Learn Geography: Glossary |last=OERI |first=U.S. Department of Education, Office of Educational Research and Improvement |authorlink=Office of Educational Research and Improvement |date=October 1996 |work=Helping Your Child Learn Geography |publisher=U.S. Department of Education |location=Washington, DC |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525054937/http://www2.ed.gov/pubs/parents/Geography/glossary.html |archivedate=May 25, 2013 |accessdate=April 16, 2013 |deadurl=yes |df=}}</ref>}}

<span id="accessibility resource"></span>{{term|term='''accessibility resource'''}}
{{defn|defn=A naturally emergent landscape form that eases communication between areas.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

{{term|term='''[[accessibility]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A locational characteristic that permits a place to be reached by the efforts of those at other places.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="acid rain"></span>{{term|term='''[[acid rain]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Rain that has become more acidic than normal (a [[pH]] below 5.0) as certain [[oxide]]s present as airborne pollutants are absorbed by the water droplets. The term is often applied generically to all acidic precipitation.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="active volcano"></span>{{term|term='''[[active volcano]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A volcano that is currently erupting, or one that has erupted during the last 10,000 years (the [[Holocene]]) or during recorded history.<ref name="USGS 2010">{{Citation |last=USGS |first=United States Geological Survey (USGS) |authorlink=United States Geological Survey |coauthors=|title=USGS Geography Products - Glossary |url=http://edc2.usgs.gov/pubslists/teachers-packets/volcanoes/teachgde/teachgdev.php#glossary |accessdate=September 30, 2010 |year=2010 |publisher=United States Geological Survey |location=Washington, DC |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528020039/http://edc2.usgs.gov/pubslists/teachers-packets/volcanoes/teachgde/teachgdev.php#glossary |archivedate=May 28, 2010 |df=}}</ref>}}

<span id="agricultural geography"></span>{{term|term='''[[agricultural geography]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A subdiscipline of geography which studies the spatial relationships between humans and [[agriculture]] and the cultural, political, and environmental processes that lead to parts of the Earth's surface being transformed by humans through {{gli|primary sector}} activities into agricultural landscapes.}}

{{term|term='''[[air mass]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A very large body of {{gli|atmosphere}} defined by essentially similar horizontal air temperatures and moisture conditions.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="alluvia"></span>{{term|term='''[[alluvia]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Clay, silt, gravel, or similar detrital material deposited by running water.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="alluvial soils"></span>{{term|term='''[[alluvial soil]]s'''}}
{{defn|defn=Soils deposited through the action of moving water. These soils lack {{gli|soil horizon|horizons}} and are usually highly fertile.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="altitude"></span>{{term|term='''[[altitude]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The height of an object in the {{gli|atmosphere}} above {{gli|sea level}}. Compare ''{{gli|elevation}}''.<ref name="OERI 1996"/>}}

<span id="Antarctic"></span>{{term|term='''[[Antarctic]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The region of the Earth that is south of the {{gli|Antarctic Circle}}.}}

<span id="Antarctic Circle"></span>{{term|term='''[[Antarctic Circle]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The southernmost of the Earth's two {{gli|polar circle|polar circles}} of {{gli|latitude}}, south of which the sun appears above the {{gli|horizon}} for 24 continuous hours at least once per year (and is therefore visible at midnight) and also appears at least partially below the horizon for 24 continuous hours at least once per year (and is therefore not visible at noon). Its latitude is approximately 66°33′47.1″ south of the {{gli|Equator}}. Contrast ''{{gli|Arctic Circle}}''.}}

{{term|term='''[[anthracite]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A hard coal containing little volatile matter.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

{{term|term='''[[anthropization]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The conversion of open spaces, landscapes, and natural environments by human action.}}

<span id="anticline"></span>{{term|term='''[[anticline]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A geological [[fold (geology)|fold]] that has an arch-like [[convex curve|convex]] shape and its oldest [[bed (geology)|beds]] near its center, often visible at the Earth's surface in exposed [[stratum|rock strata]].}}

<span id="antimeridian"></span>{{term|term='''[[antimeridian]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The line of {{gli|longitude}} exactly 180 degrees east or west of the {{gli|Prime Meridian}}, with which it forms a {{gli|great circle}} dividing the earth into the {{gli|Eastern Hemisphere|Eastern}} and {{gli|Western Hemisphere|Western Hemispheres}}. It is used as the approximate basis for the {{gli|International Date Line}} because it mostly passes through the open waters of the Pacific Ocean.}}

<span id="antipodes"></span>{{term|term='''[[antipodes]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A pair of points on the Earth's surface that are [[diameter|diametrically]] opposite to each other, such that a straight line connecting them would pass through the Earth's center. Such points are as far away from each other as possible, with the {{gli|great-circle distance}} between them being approximately {{convert|20000|km|mi}}.}}

<span id="aquifer"></span>{{term|term='''[[aquifer]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=An underground layer of {{gli|groundwater|water-bearing}} permeable rock, rock fractures, or unconsolidated materials such as gravel, sand, or silt.}}

<span id="archipelago"></span>{{term|term='''[[archipelago]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A collection of {{gli|island|islands}} in a sea.}}

<span id="arête"></span>{{term|term='''[[arête]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A sharp, narrow mountain {{gli|ridge}}. It often results from the erosive activity of alpine {{gli|glacier|glaciers}} flowing in adjacent {{gli|valley|valleys}}.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="arroyo"></span>{{term|term='''[[Arroyo (creek)|arroyo]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A deep gully cut by a stream that flows only part of the year; a dry {{gli|gulch}}. A term normally used only in {{gli|desert}} areas.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="Arctic"></span>{{term|term='''[[Arctic]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The region of the Earth that is north of the {{gli|Arctic Circle}}.}}

<span id="Arctic Circle"></span>{{term|term='''[[Arctic Circle]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The northernmost of the Earth's two {{gli|polar circle|polar circles}} of {{gli|latitude}}, north of which the sun appears above the {{gli|horizon}} for 24 continuous hours at least once per year (and is therefore visible at midnight) and also appears at least partially below the horizon for 24 continuous hours at least once per year (and is therefore not visible at noon). Its latitude is approximately 66°33′47.1″ north of the {{gli|Equator}}. Contrast ''{{gli|Antarctic Circle}}''.}}

<span id="ash"></span>{{term|term='''[[Volcanic ash|ash]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Fragments less than {{convert|1/3|cm|in}} in diameter of {{gli|lava}} or rock blasted into the air by {{gli|volcano|volcanic}} explosions.<ref name="USGS 2010"/>}}

{{term|term='''[[Atlantic Seaboard fall line]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The physiographic border between the [[Piedmont (United States)|Piedmont]] and [[Atlantic coastal plain]] regions of eastern North America. The name derives from the river rapids and falls that occur as the water flows from the hard rocks of the higher piedmont onto the softer rocks of the coastal plain.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="atlas"></span>{{term|term='''[[atlas]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A bound collection of {{gli|map|maps}}.<ref name="OERI 1996"/>}}

<span id="atmosphere"></span>{{term|term='''[[atmosphere]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The mixture of gases, aerosols, solid particles, and water vapor that envelops the Earth.<ref name="USGS 2010"/>}}

<span id="atoll"></span>{{term|term='''[[atoll]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A ring-shaped [[coral reef]] that partially or completely encircles a {{gli|lagoon}}.}}

<span id="ayre"></span>{{term|term='''[[ayre (landform)|ayre]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Another name for a {{gli|shingle beach}} or other gravel-covered {{gli|spit}}, {{gli|bar}}, or {{gli|tombolo}} used primarily in the {{gli|archipelago|archipelagos}} of northern [[Scotland]].}}

<span id="azimuth"></span>{{term|term='''[[azimuth]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The angle formed between a reference vector (often {{gli|North Magnetic Pole|magnetic north}}) and a line from the observer to a point of interest projected perpendicularly to the {{gli|zenith}} on the same [[plane of reference|plane]] as the reference vector. Azimuth is usually measured in {{gli|degree|degrees}} and can be determined with a {{gli|compass}}.}}

{{glossary end}}

{{Compact ToC|side=yes|center=yes|top=yes|num=yes|extlinks=yes|seealso=yes|refs=yes|nobreak=yes|}}

==B==
{{glossary}}

<span id="backwater[river]"></span>{{term|term='''[[backwater (river)]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A part of a river in which there is little or no current.}}
<span id="badlands"></span>{{term|term='''[[badlands]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=An area of irregular {{gli|topography}} resulting from extensive wind and water erosion of [[sedimentary rock]].<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="bar"></span>{{term|term='''[[bar (river morphology)|bar]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=An elevated region of sediment such as sand or gravel which has been deposited by the flow of a {{gli|river}} or other moving body of water. See also ''{{gli|shoal}}''.}}

<span id="barrier ridge"></span>{{term|term='''[[barrier ridge]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Any steep, unnavigable {{gli|terrain}} isolating one terrain from another.}}

{{term|term='''base level'''}}
{{defn|defn=The lowest level to which a {{gli|stream}} can erode its [[stream bed|bed]]. The ultimate base level of all streams is, of course, the {{gli|sea}}.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="basin"></span>{{term|term='''[[depression (geology)|basin]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=See ''{{gli|depression}}''.}}

<span id="batholith"></span>{{term|term='''[[batholith]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A very large body of {{gli|igneous rock}}, usually [[granite]], which has been exposed by [[erosion]] of the overlying rock.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="bay"></span>{{term|term='''[[bay]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Part of a sea or lake within a wide or narrow indentation of the shoreline.}}

<span id="beach"></span>{{term|term='''[[beach]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A landform along the {{gli|coast|shoreline}} of an {{gli|ocean}}, {{gli|sea}}, {{gli|lake}}, or {{gli|river}} with a loose surface of sand, gravel, shingle, pebbles, shells, stones or coral.}}

<span id="bearing"></span>{{term|term='''[[bearing (navigation)|bearing]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The direction or position of an object, or the direction of an object's movement, relative to a fixed point. It is typically measured in {{gli|degree|degrees}} and can be determined with a {{gli|compass}}, where {{gli|North Magnetic Pole|magnetic north}} is by convention defined as having a bearing of zero degrees.}}

<span id="bedrock"></span>{{term|term='''[[bedrock]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The solid rock in the Earth's {{gli|crust}} that underlies all soil or other loose material; the rock material that breaks down eventually to form soil.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="bight"></span>{{term|term='''[[bight (geography)|bight]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A bend or curve in a coastline, river, or other geographical feature typically indicating a large, open {{gli|bay}}. It is shallower than a {{gli|sound}}.}}

<span id="biological diversity"></span>{{term|term='''[[Biodiversity|biological diversity]]'''}}
{{ghat|Also called '''biodiversity'''.}}
{{defn|defn=A concept recognising the variety of life forms in an area of the Earth and the ecological interdependence of these life forms.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="biogeography"></span>{{term|term='''[[biogeography]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The study of the distribution of [[biology|biological]] [[species]] and [[ecosystems]] in geographic space and through geological time.}}

<span id="biosphere"></span>{{term|term='''[[biosphere]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The realm of all living things.<ref name="USGS 2010"/>}}

<span id="biota"></span>{{term|term='''[[Biota (ecology)|biota]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The animal and plant life of a region considered as a total ecological entity.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

{{term|term='''[[bituminous]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A soft coal that, when heated, yields considerable volatile matter.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="blowout"></span>{{term|term='''[[blowout (geomorphology)|blowout]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A sandy {{gli|depression}} formed when [[wind]] [[wind erosion|erodes]] into patches of bare sand on otherwise vegetation-stabilized {{gli|dune|sand dunes}} at the margins of coastal and arid ecosystems.}}

<span id="bocage"></span>{{term|term='''[[bocage]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A landscape of mixed woodland and [[pasture]], with fields and winding country lanes sunken between low, narrow ridges and banks surmounted by tall, thick [[hedgerow]]s, especially as found in rural parts of western Europe.}}

<span id="body of water"></span>{{term|term='''[[body of water]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Any significant accumulation of water, either natural or artificial, on the surface of the Earth. Bodies of water may hold or contain water, as with {{gli|lake|lakes}} and {{gli|ocean|oceans}}, or they may collect and move water from one place to another, as with {{gli|river|rivers}}, {{gli|stream|streams}}, and other {{gli|waterway|waterways}}.}}

<span id="bootheel"></span>{{term|term='''bootheel'''}}
{{defn|defn=See ''{{gli|salient}}''.}}

<span id="border"></span>{{term|term='''[[border]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The geographical boundary of a political entity or legal jurisdiction, such as a {{gli|country}}, {{gli|state}}, or other [[subnational entity]].<ref name="OERI 1996"/>}}

<span id="borough"></span>{{term|term='''[[borough]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

{{term|term='''break-in-bulk point'''}}
{{defn|defn=A transfer point on a transport route where the mode of transport or type of carrier changes and where large-volume shipments are reduced in size. For example, goods may be unloaded from a ship and transferred to trucks at an ocean port.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="built environment"></span>{{term|term='''[[built environment]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The human-made spaces that provide the setting for human activity, in which people live, work, and recreate on a day-to-day basis.}}

<span id="butte"></span>{{term|term='''[[butte]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=An isolated {{gli|hill}} or {{gli|mountain}} with steep or precipitous sides, usually having a smaller summit area than a {{gli|mesa}}.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

{{glossary end}}

