==F==

{{glossary}}
{{term|term='''[[fall line]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A [[geomorphology|geomorphologic]] [[unconformity]] between an upland region of relatively hard [[basement (geology)|crystalline basement rock]] and a [[coastal plain]] of softer [[sedimentary rock]].}}

{{term|term='''[[fallow]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Agricultural land that is plowed or tilled but left unseeded during a growing season. Fallowing is usually done to conserve moisture.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="fault"></span>{{term|term='''[[Fault (geology)|fault]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A fracture in the Earth's crust accompanied by a displacement of one side of the fracture.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

{{term|term='''[[fault-block mountain]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A mountain mass created by either the uplift of land between faults or the subsidence of land outside the faults.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

{{term|term='''[[fault zone]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=An area of numerous fractures in the Earth's crust along which movement has occurred. The movement may be in any direction and involve material on either or both sides of the fractures.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

{{term|term='''[[federation]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A form of government in which powers and functions are divided between a central government and a number of political subdivisions that have a significant degree of political autonomy.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="fen"></span>{{term|term='''[[fen]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

<span id="field"></span>{{term|term='''[[field (geography)|field]]'''}}
{{ghat|Also called a '''spatially dependent variable'''.}}
{{defn|defn=A quantity that can be theoretically assigned to any point of space, such as temperature, soil moisture, or population density. Both scalar and vector fields are found in geographic applications, although the former is more common.}}

<span id="figure of the Earth"></span>{{term|term='''[[figure of the Earth]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The size and shape of the Earth as studied in {{gli|geodesy}}. Applications requiring varying levels of precision have led to the development of many different models of the Earth, ranging from simple spheres to much more accurate approximations such as {{gli|geoid|geoids}}.}}

<span id="firth"></span>{{term|term='''[[firth]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

{{term|term='''[[fish ladder]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A series of shallow steps down which water is allowed to flow; designed to permit salmon to circumvent artificial barriers such as power dams as the salmon swim upstream to spawn.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

{{term|term='''[[fjord]]'''}}
{{ghat|Also spelled '''fiord'''.}}
{{defn|defn=A long, narrow marine inlet with steep sides or {{gli|cliff|cliffs}} created by glacial erosion.}}

<span id="floodplain"></span>{{term|term='''[[floodplain]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A broad, flat area of land adjacent to a {{gli|river}} or {{gli|stream}} which is leveled by annual flooding and by the lateral and downstream movement of {{gli|meander|meanders}}.}}

{{term|term='''focality'''}}
{{defn|defn=The characteristic of a place that follows from its interconnections with more than one other place. When interaction within a region comes together at a single place (i.e., when the movement focuses on that location), the place is said to possess focality.}}

<span id="forest"></span>{{term|term='''[[forest]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Any large area dominated by [[community (biology)|communities]] of trees.}}

{{term|term='''functional diversity'''}}
{{defn|defn=The characteristic of a place where a variety of different activities (economic, political, or social, for example) occurs; most often associated with urban places.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

{{glossary end}}

