==H==

{{glossary}}
<span id="hamlet"></span>{{term|term='''[[hamlet (place)|hamlet]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A small human settlement, variably defined as one the size of a {{gli|town}}, {{gli|village}}, or {{gli|parish}} or as a smaller subdivision of or satellite entity to a larger settlement.}}

<span id="hanging valley"></span>{{term|term='''[[hanging valley]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

{{term|term='''[[harmonic tremor]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Continuous rhythmic earthquakes in the Earth's upper {{gli|lithosphere}} that can be detected by {{gli|seismograph|seismographs}}. Harmonic tremors often precede or accompany {{gli|volcano|volcanic eruptions}}.<ref name="USGS 2010"/>}}

<span id="heading"></span>{{term|term='''[[heading (navigation)|heading]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

<span id="headland"></span>{{term|term='''[[headland]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A high coastal {{gli|promontory}} that extends out into a body of water, often surrounded by steep {{gli|cliff|cliffs}}. A very large headland is often called a {{gli|cape}}.}}

<span id="hearth"></span>{{term|term='''[[hearth]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The source area of any innovation. The source area from which an idea, crop, artifact, or good is diffused to other areas.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="heartland"></span>{{term|term='''[[wikt:heartland|heartland]]'''}}
{{defn|no=1|defn=The central part of a {{gli|region}}.}}
{{defn|no=2|defn=A part of a region considered essential to the viability and survival of the whole.}}

<span id="heath"></span>{{term|term='''[[heath]]'''}}
{{ghat|Also called '''heathland'''.}}
{{defn|defn=A shrubland habitat found mainly on free-draining, infertile, acidic soils and characterized by open, low-growing, woody vegetation.}}

<span id="hedgerow"></span>{{term|term='''[[hedgerow]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

<span id="hemisphere"></span>{{term|term='''[[Hemispheres of the Earth|hemisphere]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Half of the Earth, usually conceived as resulting from the division of the globe into two equal parts of either {{gli|Northern Hemisphere|north}} and {{gli|Southern Hemisphere|south}} or {{gli|Eastern Hemisphere|east}} and {{gli|Western Hemisphere|west}}.<ref name="OERI 1996"/>}}

<span id="highland"></span>{{term|term='''[[highland]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

<span id="highway"></span>{{term|term='''[[highway]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

<span id="hill"></span>{{term|term='''[[hill]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Any landform that extends above the surrounding {{gli|terrain}}; a hill is generally considered less steep than a {{gli|mountain}}.}}

<span id="hillock"></span>{{term|term='''[[hillock]]'''}}
{{ghat|Also called a '''knoll'''.}}
{{defn|defn=A small {{gli|hill}}.}}

{{term|term='''[[hinterland]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=An area that is tributary to a place and linked to that place through lines of exchange or interaction.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="historical geography"></span>{{term|term='''[[historical geography]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A branch of {{gli|human geography}} that studies the ways in which geographic phenomena have changed over time, especially (though not necessarily limited to) geographic change as it relates to human activity.}}

<span id="hogback"></span>{{term|term='''[[hogback (geology)|hogback]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

<span id="horizon"></span>{{term|term='''[[horizon]]'''}}
{{ghat|Also called the '''skyline'''.}}
{{defn|defn=The apparent line that separates the ground from the sky, dividing all visible directions into two categories: those that intersect the Earth's surface and those that do not. When not obscured by buildings, trees, or mountains, the true horizon can be useful in navigation and determining positional orientation.}}

<span id="hotspot"></span>{{term|term='''[[Hotspot (geology)|hotspot]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=An area in the middle of a {{gli|lithospheric plate}} where {{gli|magma}} rises from the mantle and erupts at the Earth's surface. {{gli|Volcano|Volcanoes}} sometimes occur above a hotspot.<ref name="USGS 2010"/>}}

<span id="human geography"></span>{{term|term='''[[human geography]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The branch of geography that studies humans and their communities, cultures, economies, and interactions with the environment by examining their relations with and across space and place. Along with {{gli|physical geography}}, it is one of the two major subfields of geography.}}

<span id="hummock"></span>{{term|term='''[[hummock]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A small {{gli|knoll}} or {{gli|mound}}, typically less than {{convert|15|m|ft}} in height and situated above an otherwise level ground surface.}}

{{term|term='''[[humus]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Partially decomposed organic soil material.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="hydrography"></span>{{term|term='''[[hydrography]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The study of the surface waters of the Earth.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="hydrosphere"></span>{{term|term='''[[hydrosphere]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The totality of the water found on, under, and above the Earth's surface in liquid, solid, and gaseous forms, including all {{gli|ocean|oceans}}, {{gli|lake|lakes}}, {{gli|river|rivers}}, and {{gli|stream|streams}}, as well as all ice and {{gli|glacier|glaciers}} and subsurface {{gli|groundwater}}. Some definitions restrict the hydrosphere to liquid water only, instead placing solid forms in the {{gli|cryosphere}} and gaseous forms in the {{gli|atmosphere}}.<ref name="USGS 2010"/>}}

{{glossary end}}

