{{defn|no=1|defn=A wall of wooden stakes used as a defensive barrier.}}
{{defn|no=2|defn=A line of bold {{gli|cliff|cliffs}}, especially one showing [[columnar basalt|basaltic columns]].<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="panhandle"></span>{{term|term='''[[salient (geography)|panhandle]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=See ''{{gli|salient}}''.}}

<span id="parish"></span>{{term|term='''[[parish]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

<span id="permafrost"></span>{{term|term='''[[permafrost]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A permanently frozen layer of soil;<ref name="IIP 2008"/> permanently frozen ground at high {{gli|latitude}} and high {{gli|elevation}}.<ref name="USGS 2010"/>}}

<span id="peninsula"></span>{{term|term='''[[peninsula]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A piece of land surrounded by water along the majority of its border while still being connected to a {{gli|mainland}} from which it extends.}}

<span id="photogrammetry"></span>{{term|term='''[[photogrammetry]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

<span id="physical geography"></span>{{term|term='''[[physical geography]]'''}}
{{ghat|Also called '''physiography''' or '''geosystems'''.}}
{{defn|defn=The branch of geography that studies processes and patterns in the [[natural environment]], such as the {{gli|atmosphere}}, {{gli|hydrosphere}}, {{gli|geosphere}}, and {{gli|biosphere}}, as opposed to the cultural or {{gli|built environment}}. Along with {{gli|human geography}}, it is one of the two major subfields of geography.}}

<span id="physiographic region"></span>{{term|term='''[[Physiographic regions of the world|physiographic region]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A portion of the Earth's surface with a common {{gli|topography}} and common morphology.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="physiography"></span>{{term|term='''[[physiography]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Another name for ''{{gli|physical geography}}''.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="piedmont"></span>{{term|term='''[[foothills|piedmont]]'''}}
{{ghat|Also called '''foothills'''.}}
{{defn|no=1|defn=Any geographic region lying or formed at the base of {{gli|mountain|mountains}}.}}
{{defn|no=2|defn=In the [[Southeastern United States]], a broad region extending from the [[Blue Ridge Mountains]] to the [[Atlantic coastal plain]].<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="pit crater"></span>{{term|term='''[[pit crater]]'''}}
{{ghat|Also called a '''subsidence crater''' or '''collapse crater'''.}}
{{defn|defn=A type of {{gli|crater}} formed by the sinking or collapse of the surface lying above a void or empty chamber. Pit craters are similar to {{gli|caldera|calderas}} and are often associated with volcanic activity, but lack the [[ejecta]] deposits and {{gli|lava}} flows of {{gli|volcanic crater|volcanic craters}}.}}

{{term|term='''[[place identity]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

<span id="plain"></span>{{term|term='''[[plain]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Any broad, flat expanse of land that generally does not show significant variation in {{gli|elevation}}.}}

<span id="plate tectonics"></span>{{term|term='''[[plate tectonics]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A geologic theory that the bending (folding) and breaking (faulting) of the solid surface of the Earth results from the slow movement of large sections of that surface called plates.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="plateau"></span>{{term|term='''[[plateau]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=An area of {{gli|highland}} consisting of relatively flat terrain that is significantly higher than the surrounding landscape, often with one or more sides with steep slopes. Also sometimes called a ''high plain'' or ''tableland''.}}

{{term|term='''platted land'''}}
{{defn|defn=Land that has been divided into {{gli|surveying|surveyed}} lots.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="plumb line"></span>{{term|term='''[[plumb line]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

{{term|term='''[[plural society]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A situation in which two or more {{gli|culture}} groups occupy the same territory but maintain their separate cultural identities.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="polar circle"></span>{{term|term='''[[polar circle]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Either of the two circles of {{gli|latitude}} enclosing the Earth's {{gli|polar region|polar regions}}: the {{gli|Arctic Circle}} in the Northern Hemisphere and the {{gli|Antarctic Circle}} in the Southern Hemisphere.}}

<span id="polar ice cap"></span>{{term|term='''[[polar ice cap]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

<span id="polar region"></span>{{term|term='''[[polar region]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Either of the two high-latitude regions surrounding the Earth's geographical poles (the {{gli|North Geographic Pole|North}} and {{gli|South Geographic Pole|South Poles}}), which are characterized by frigid climates and extensive {{gli|polar ice cap|polar ice caps}}. The polar region of the Northern Hemisphere is often simply called the {{gli|Arctic}} and that of the Southern Hemisphere is called the {{gli|Antarctic}}.}}

{{term|term='''[[pole of inaccessibility]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

<span id="political geography"></span>{{term|term='''[[political geography]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The study of both the spatially uneven outcomes of [[politics|political]] processes and the ways in which political processes are themselves affected by spatial structures. A subdiscipline of {{gli|human geography}}, its primary concerns can be summarized as the relationships between people, state, and territory.}}

{{term|term='''polynodal'''}}
{{defn|defn=Many-centered.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="pond"></span>{{term|term='''[[pond]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A natural or artificial {{gli|body of water|body}} of [[standing water]] that is usually smaller than a {{gli|lake}}.}}

<span id="populated place"></span>{{term|term='''[[populated place]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A place or area with clustered or scattered buildings and a permanent human population (a {{gli|city}}, {{gli|settlement}}, {{gli|town}}, or {{gli|village}}) that is referenced with {{gli|geographic coordinate system|geographic coordinates}}.<ref name="USGS 2010"/>}}

<span id="population"></span>{{term|term='''[[population]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A collection of organisms of the same group or species which live in a particular geographical area. In the context of geography, it often refers to a collection of humans and is represented at the most basic level as the number of people in a given geographically or politically defined space, such as a {{gli|city}}, {{gli|town}}, {{gli|region}}, {{gli|country}}, or the entire [[world population|world]].}}

<span id="population geography"></span>{{term|term='''[[population geography]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

<span id="positioning system"></span>{{term|term='''[[positioning system]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

{{term|term='''[[post-industrial]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=An economy that gains its basic character from economic activities developed primarily after manufacturing grew to predominance. Most notable would be quaternary economic patterns.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="pothole"></span>{{term|term='''[[pothole (landform)|pothole]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

{{term|term='''[[Precambrian|Precambrian rock]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The oldest rocks, generally more than 600 million years old.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="prevailing winds"></span>{{term|term='''[[prevailing winds]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The direction from which winds most frequently blow at a specific geographic location.<ref name="USGS 2010"/>}}

<span id="primary sector"></span>{{term|term='''[[primary sector]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=That portion of a region's economy devoted to the extraction of basic materials (e.g., mining, lumbering, agriculture).<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="Prime Meridian"></span>{{term|term='''[[Prime Meridian]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The imaginary line running from north to south through the [[Royal Observatory, Greenwich|Royal Observatory]] in [[Greenwich, England]] which is assigned a {{gli|longitude}} of 0 degrees and is therefore used as the reference point for all other lines of longitude.<ref name="OERI 1996"/>}}

<span id="promontory"></span>{{term|term='''[[promontory]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A raised mass of land that projects into a {{gli|lowland}} or a {{gli|body of water}}. Compare ''{{gli|headland}}'' and ''{{gli|cape}}''.}}

<span id="protected area"></span>{{term|term='''[[protected area]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Any clearly defined geographic space in which human occupation or the exploitation of resources is limited or forbidden through legal or other effective means because of the area's recognized natural, ecological, cultural, or historical value.}}

<span id="province"></span>{{term|term='''[[province]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A type of second-level administrative division within a {{gli|country}} or {{gli|state|federal state}}.}}

<span id="psychogeography"></span>{{term|term='''[[psychogeography]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

<span id="public land"></span>{{term|term='''[[public land]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

{{term|term='''[[pueblo]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A type of Indian village constructed by some tribes in the southwestern United States. A large community dwelling, divided into many rooms, up to five stories high, and usually made of adobe. This is also a Spanish word for town or village.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

{{glossary end}}

