==T==

{{glossary}}
<span id="taiga"></span>{{term|term='''[[taiga]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A moist subarctic coniferous {{gli|forest}} that begins where the {{gli|tundra}} ends and is dominated by spruces and firs.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="tarn"></span>{{term|term='''[[tarn (lake)|tarn]]'''}}
{{ghat|Also called a '''corrie loch'''.}}
{{defn|defn=A mountain {{gli|lake}} or pool of water formed in a {{gli|cirque}} excavated by a {{gli|glacier}}. A {{gli|moraine}} may form a natural {{gli|dam}} below a tarn.}}

{{term|term='''[[temperature inversion]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=An increase in temperature with height above the Earth's surface, a reversal of the normal pattern.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="tephra"></span>{{term|term='''[[tephra]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=Solid material of all sizes explosively ejected from a {{gli|volcano}} into the atmosphere.<ref name="USGS 2010"/>}}

<span id="terrain"></span>{{term|term='''[[terrain]]'''}}
{{ghat|Also called '''topographical relief''' or simply '''relief'''.}}
{{defn|defn=The vertical and horizontal dimensions of a land surface, usually as expressed in terms of {{gli|elevation}}, [[slope]], and orientation of geographical features.}}

<span id="territorial waters"></span>{{term|term='''[[territorial waters]]'''}}
{{defn|no=1|defn=A concept of the [[Law of the Sea]] defined as a belt of {{gli|coast|coastal}} waters extending at most {{convert|12|nmi|km}} from the designated [[baseline (sea)|baseline]] (usually defined as the mean low-water line) for a coastal {{gli|state}} and regarded as the sovereign {{gli|territory}} of the state.}}
{{defn|no=2|defn=Any area of water over which a state has legal jurisdiction, including [[internal waters]], the [[exclusive economic zone]], and potentially others.}}

<span id="territory"></span>{{term|term='''[[Territory (country subdivision)|territory]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A specific area or portion of the Earth's surface; similar to though distinct from a {{gli|region}}.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="tertiary sector"></span>{{term|term='''[[tertiary sector]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=That portion of a region's economy devoted to service activities (e.g., retail and wholesale operations, transportation, insurance).<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="thalweg"></span>{{term|term='''[[thalweg]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The line of lowest {{gli|elevation}} within a {{gli|valley}} or [[watercourse]]. Thalwegs often acquire special significance in {{gli|political geography}} because disputed {{gli|border|borders}} along rivers are often defined as the river's thalweg.}}

<span id="tide"></span>{{term|term='''[[tide]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The periodic rise and fall of {{gli|sea level|sea levels}} caused by the combined effects of the gravitational forces exerted by the [[Moon]] and the [[Sun]] and the [[Earth's rotation]].}}

<span id="till"></span>{{term|term='''[[glacial till|till]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=See ''{{gli|glacial till}}''.}}

{{term|term='''[[time distance]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A time measure of how far apart places are (how long does it take to travel from place A to place B?). This may be contrasted with other distance metrics such as geographic distance (how far is it?) and cost-distance (how much will it cost to get there?).<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="time geography"></span>{{term|term='''[[time geography]]'''}}
{{ghat|Also called '''time-space geography'''.}}
{{defn|defn=An interdisciplinary perspective, [[ontology|ontological]] framework, and [[visual language]] in which space and time are used as basic dimensions of analysis of dynamic processes and events, including social and ecological interactions, environmental changes, and biographies of individuals.}}

<span id="time zone"></span>{{term|term='''[[time zone]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A region of the globe that observes a uniform [[standard time]] for legal, commercial, and social purposes.}}

<span id="tombolo"></span>{{term|term='''[[tombolo]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

<span id="topographic map"></span>{{term|term='''[[topographic map]]'''}}
{{ghat|Also called a '''relief map'''.}}
{{defn|defn=A map that uses [[contour line]]s to represent the three-dimensional features of a landscape on a two-dimensional surface.<ref name="USGS 2010"/>}}

<span id="topographical relief"></span>{{term|term='''[[topographical relief]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=See ''{{gli|terrain}}''.}}

<span id="topographic isolation"></span>{{term|term='''[[topographic isolation]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The minimum {{gli|great-circle distance}} between the {{gli|summit}} of a {{gli|mountain}} or {{gli|hill}} and a point of equal {{gli|elevation}}, representing a radius of dominance in which the summit is the highest point.}}

<span id="topographic prominence"></span>{{term|term='''[[topographic prominence]]'''}}
{{ghat|Also called '''autonomous height''', '''relative height''', or '''shoulder drop'''.}}
{{defn|defn=A measure of the independence of a {{gli|mountain}} or {{gli|hill}} defined as the vertical distance between its {{gli|summit}} and the lowest {{gli|contour lines|contour line}} encircling it but containing no higher summit within it or, equivalently, the difference between the {{gli|elevation}} of the summit and the elevation of the {{gli|key col}}. Mountains with high prominence tend to be the highest points in their vicinity.}}

<span id="topography"></span>{{term|term='''[[topography]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The physical features of a place, or the study and depiction of physical features, including {{gli|terrain|terrain relief}}.<ref name="OERI 1996"/>}}

<span id="toponymy"></span>{{term|term='''[[toponymy]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The study of placenames (known as ''toponyms''), their origins, meanings, use, and typology.}}

<span id="tor"></span>{{term|term='''[[tor (rock formation)|tor]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=}}

<span id="town"></span>{{term|term='''[[town]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A medium-sized human {{gli|settlement}} that is generally larger than a {{gli|village}} but smaller than a {{gli|city}}, though the criteria for distinguishing a town vary considerably in different parts of the world.}}

{{term|term='''[[township and range]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The rectangular system of land subdivision of much of the agriculturally settled United States west of the Appalachian Mountains established by the [[Land Ordinance of 1785]].<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

{{term|term='''transferability'''}}
{{defn|defn=The extent to which a good or service can be moved from one location to another; the relative capacity for spatial interaction.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

{{term|term='''[[transhumance]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The seasonal movement of people and animals in search of pasture. Commonly, winters are spent in snow-free lowlands and summers in the cooler uplands.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="tree line"></span>{{term|term='''[[tree line]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The {{gli|latitude|latitudinal}} or {{gli|elevation|elevational}} limit of normal tree growth. Beyond this limit (i.e. closer to the {{gli|polar region|poles}} or at higher elevations) climatic conditions are too severe for such growth and trees are stunted or entirely absent.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="tributary"></span>{{term|term='''[[tributary]]'''}}
{{ghat|Also called an '''affluent'''.}}
{{defn|defn=A {{gli|stream}} or {{gli|river}} that flows into a larger stream or {{gli|main stem}} or a {{gli|lake}}, rather than directly into a {{gli|sea}} or {{gli|ocean}}. Contrast ''{{gli|distributary}}''.}}

<span id="Tropic of Cancer"></span>{{term|term='''[[Tropic of Cancer]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The northernmost {{gli|latitude|circle of latitude}} on the Earth at which the Sun appears {{gli|zenith|directly overhead}} at its culmination, which lies approximately 23.4 degrees north of the {{gli|Equator}}. Its southern equivalent is the {{gli|Tropic of Capricorn}}.}}

<span id="Tropic of Capricorn"></span>{{term|term='''[[Tropic of Capricorn]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=The southernmost {{gli|latitude|circle of latitude}} on the Earth at which the Sun appears {{gli|zenith|directly overhead}} at its culmination, which lies approximately 23.4 degrees south of the {{gli|Equator}}. Its northern equivalent is the {{gli|Tropic of Cancer}}.}}

<span id="tropics"></span>{{term|term='''[[tropics]]'''}}
{{ghat|Also called the '''tropical zone''' or '''torrid zone'''.}}
{{defn|defn=The region of the Earth's surface surrounding the {{gli|Equator}} and bounded by the Tropic of Cancer (23.4° N latitude) and the Tropic of Capricorn (23.4° S latitude). It is characterized by high annual precipitation and the absence of any significant seasonal variation in temperature. The term is often used more broadly to describe any area possessing what is considered a hot, humid climate.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

<span id="true north"></span>{{term|term='''[[true north]]'''}}
{{ghat|Also called '''geodetic north'''.}}
{{defn|defn=The direction along the Earth's surface towards the {{gli|North Geographic Pole|Geographic North Pole}}. Geodetic true north differs from {{gli|magnetic north}} and {{gli|grid north}}, and also very slightly from astronomical true north, which is based on the direction of the north {{gli|celestial pole}}.}}

<span id="tundra"></span>{{term|term='''[[tundra]]'''}}
{{defn|defn=A treeless {{gli|plain}} characteristic of the {{gli|Arctic|arctic}} and subarctic regions.<ref name="IIP 2008"/>}}

{{glossary end}}

