[[File:Middletown Friends Meeting House Lima PA.jpg|thumb|Middletown Friends Meeting House Lima PA]] [[File:Middletown Preparative Friends Meeting House, Middletown Road, 1 mile north of Pennell Road (Route 452), Lima, Delaware County, PA HABS PA-6655-20.tif|thumb|Interior of Middletown Friends Meetinghouse from Historic American Building Survey Photo]] [[File:Middletown Preparative Friends Meeting House, Middletown Road, 1 mile north of Pennell Road (Route 452), Lima, Delaware County, PA HABS PA-6655-21.tif|thumb|Benches inside Middletown Friends Meetinghouse from Historic American Building Survey Photo]] '''Middletown Friends Meetinghouse''' is a Historic [[Quaker]] meeting house at 435 Middletown Road in [[Lima, Pennsylvania|Lima]], [[Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Delaware County]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States]]. It is one of the oldest Friends meetinghouses in what was originally [[Chester County, Pennsylvania|Chester County]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lavoie|first1=Catherine|title=Historic American Buildings Survey|url=https://cdn.loc.gov/master/pnp/habshaer/pa/pa3800/pa3803/data/pa3803data.pdf|website=www.loc.gov|publisher=U.S. Department of Interior|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref>
The first mention of an organized Friends meeting in Middletown Township was in 1686.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Jordan|first1=John W|title=A History of Delaware County, Pennsylvania and Its People|date=1912|publisher=Lewis Historical Publishing Company|location=New York|page=396|url=https://archive.org/stream/historyofdelawar02jord#page/396/mode/2up|accessdate=20 June 2017}}</ref> The location and construction of a meetinghouse was noted in 1699 and the Middletown Friends Meetinghouse was completed in 1702.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ashmeade|first1=Henry Graham|title=History of Delaware County, Pennsylvania|date=1884|publisher=L.H. Everts & Co.|location=Philadelphia|page=613|url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924006215655|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref>
During the 1790s, the building was doubled in size through the addition of a separate apartment. In the 1880s, the meetinghouse was reconfigured creating a more church-like appearance and orientation.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lavoie|first1=Catherine|title=Historic American Buildings Survey|url=https://cdn.loc.gov/master/pnp/habshaer/pa/pa3800/pa3803/data/pa3803data.pdf|website=www.cdn.loc.gov|publisher=U.S. Department of Interior|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref>
The Middletown Friends meetinghouse is an active worship center.<ref>{{cite web|title=Middletown Quakers website|url=http://www.middletownquakers.org/|website=middletownquakers.org|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref>
[[John Edwards (Pennsylvania politician)|John Edwards]], the Congressman from Pennsylvania is interred at the Middletown Friends Meetinghouse cemetery.<ref>{{cite web|title=Edward, John (1786 - 1843)|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=E000074|website=www.bioguide.congress.gov|accessdate=26 April 2018}}</ref>
